data.content:
These are two separate C# 15 breaking changes:

**1. `DynamicOps.cs` — Short-circuit operators with `dynamic`**

C# 15 now correctly rejects `&&`/`||` when one operand is `dynamic` and the other has user-defined `operator true`/`operator false`. Previously the compiler incorrectly bound this at compile time, ignoring the `dynamic` operand. Fix by avoiding the short-circuit:

```csharp
void Apply(IFilter left, dynamic right)
{
    // Option A: use explicit operator calls
    if (CompositeFilter.op_True(left))
        var combined = left;
    else
        var combined = left & right;  // non-short-circuit '&' still works with dynamic

    // Option B: cast away dynamic
    var combined = left && (IFilter)right;
}
```

**2. `RefHelper.cs` — CS0518 with `ref readonly` lambda return**

C# 15 now emits a `RequiresLocationAttribute` on `ref readonly` lambda returns. If your target framework's runtime libraries don't yet include this attribute, you get CS0518. Fixes:

```csharp
// Option A: use a named method instead of a lambda
static ref readonly int GetValue() => ref value;

// Option B: drop 'readonly' if mutability is acceptable
var fn = ref int () => ref value;

// Option C: define the missing attribute yourself
namespace System.Runtime.CompilerServices
{
    [AttributeUsage(AttributeTargets.Parameter | AttributeTargets.ReturnValue)]
    sealed class RequiresLocationAttribute : Attribute { }
}
```

**TL;DR:** The first is a correctness fix — the old behavior silently produced wrong code with `dynamic`. The second is a new metadata attribute requirement for `ref readonly` lambdas that your runtime may not ship yet.
